/*
Problem: Rotate Image

Given an n x n 2D matrix representing an image, rotate the image by
90 degrees clockwise in-place.

Approach:
1. Take the transpose of the matrix.
2. Reverse every row.
3. This results in a 90° clockwise rotation without using extra space.
*/

class Solution {
public:
    void rotate(vector<vector<int>>& matrix) {

        int n = matrix.size();

        // Transpose the matrix
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for(int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
                swap(matrix[i][j], matrix[j][i]);
            }
        }

        // Reverse every row
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            reverse(matrix[i].begin(), matrix[i].end());
        }
    }
};

/*
Time Complexity: O(n^2)
Space Complexity: O(1)

Mistakes I Made:
1. Initially tried to find a direct relation:
   (i, j) -> (j, n - i - 1), but couldn't perform the rotation in-place.
2. Thought an extra matrix might be required, but the problem explicitly asked for O(1) extra space.
3. While taking the transpose, I first used:
      for(int j = 0; j < n; j++)
   which swapped each pair twice and restored the original matrix.
4. Corrected the transpose by starting the inner loop from:
      j = i + 1
   so each pair is swapped exactly once.
5. Was confused about whether to reverse rows or columns after transpose.
   Finally understood that:
      - Transpose + Reverse Rows  -> 90° Clockwise Rotation
      - Transpose + Reverse Columns -> 90° Anti-Clockwise Rotation

Possible Optimization:
This is already the optimal solution.
Time Complexity: O(n²)
Space Complexity: O(1)
*/
